   <m:mtext>Z</m:mtext>
   <m:mn>0</m:mn>
  </m:msup>
  </m:mrow>
</m:math>  bosons), carriers of the weak nuclear force, are nearly 1,000 times more massive than pions, carriers of the strong nuclear force. Simultaneously, the distance that the weak nuclear force can be transmitted is approximately  <m:math>
 <m:mrow>
  <m:mfrac>
   <m:mn>1</m:mn>
   <m:mrow>
    <m:mn>1,000</m:mn></m:mrow>
  </m:mfrac>
  </m:mrow>
</m:math>  times the strong force transmission distance. Unlike carrier particles, which have a limited range, the photon is a massless particle that has no limit to the transmission distance of the electromagnetic force. This relationship leads scientists to understand that the yet-unfound graviton is likely massless as well.</para><table id="Table_23_02" summary="The table has four columns for force, carrier particle, range, and relative strength. The four rows of the table are for the four forces: gravity, electromagnetic, weak, and strong. The gravity force has a theorized carrier particle called the graviton and has an infinite range. The electromagnetic force has a carrier particle called the photon and has an infinite range. The weak force has carrier particles called the W and Z bosons and has a range less than 10-18 meters. The strong force has a carrier particle called the Pi Meson, now known as a gluon, and has a range less than 10-15 meters. Relative force values are identical to those listed in [Table_23_01_Force]."><title>Carrier particles and their relative masses compared to pions for the four fundamental forces</title>
